========================================================================
PART C: c Fine-Tuning -- Why D_eff < D_Apollonian
========================================================================

  The actual primes in S_{beta_0} grow SLOWER than Apollonian scaling predicts.
  We can measure the effective dimension D_eff from the observed prime sequence:

  Apollonian rule backwards: if log(p_{n+1}) = log(p_n) + (log p_n)^(1/D_eff)
  then (log p_{n+1} - log p_n)^(D_eff) = log(p_n)
  So D_eff = log(log p_n) / log(log p_{n+1} - log p_n)

  From certified p4=191, p5=3993746143633:
    log(p4) = 5.252273
    log(p5) = 29.01575079
    delta = log(p5) - log(p4) = 23.763477
    D_eff(p4->p5) = log(log p4) / log(delta) = log(5.2523) / log(23.7635)
                  = 1.658661 / 3.168150
                  = 0.523542

  D_eff = 0.5235 vs D_Apollonian = 1.3057
  D_eff < D_Apollonian: the actual primes grow SLOWER than the gasket predicts.
  At D_eff = 0.5235, the scaling gives smaller increments.

  The critical threshold: D must reach D_Apollonian = 1.3057
  for S_beta to 'hit the gasket' and g to grow toward 5070+.

  The universe fine-tuned c/10^6 = 299.792458 to give beta_0 with
  D_eff = 0.5235 < 1.3057. The repunit error eps=1/625.789
  (from c/beta_0) is precisely what keeps D_eff below the gasket threshold.
  This is the price of keeping RH hard.

